61106"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EChronic liver injury leads to progressive fibrosis through cellular activation and extracellular matrix deposition.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cells is primarily responsible for generating liver fibrosis when activated during chronic liver disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hepatocytes","Kupffer cells","Stellate cells","Sinusoidal endothelial cells","Bile duct epithelial cells"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatocytes\u003C/strong\u003E are the main functional cells of the liver responsible for protein synthesis, bile production, and metabolism. \u003Cstrong\u003EKupffer cells\u003C/strong\u003E are liver-specific macrophages that play a role in inflammation and immune response. \u003Cstrong\u003EStellate cells\u003C/strong\u003E (also known as Ito cells) are the key mediators of liver fibrosis - when activated by liver injury, they transform into myofibroblast-like cells that produce excessive amounts of collagen and other extracellular matrix proteins. \u003Cstrong\u003ESinusoidal endothelial cells\u003C/strong\u003E line the liver sinusoids and regulate blood flow. \u003Cstrong\u003EBile duct epithelial cells\u003C/strong\u003E form the bile ducts but do not directly contribute to fibrosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hepatic stellate cells (Ito cells) are the main cells responsible for liver fibrosis when activated in chronic liver disease.","Activated stellate cells transform into myofibroblast-like cells that produce excess collagen and other extracellular matrix proteins."],"references":["Joseph A, Samant H. Jaundice. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31334972","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wile